… Bans commercial vehicles, tricycles, Motorcycles, Market, Mosques, Churches Operations  The Kwara state government has placed a total ban on socio- economic activities in the state to curb the spread of coronavirus in the state. The government had asked the state civil servants to work from home since Monday, while it also ordered the closure of all schools from primary to tertiary institutions. The latest ban on socio- economic activities involved the operations of all motor parks, markets, commercial vehicles, motorcycles and tricycles. Activities at places of worships such as mosques and churches, social functions and engagements have also been banned. The state deputy governor who is also the chairman, technical committee on Covid-19, Mr  Kayode Alabi announced the new measures in Ilorin, the state capital yesterday. Alabi  added that the new measures would be enforced by the security operatives, noting that “the locking down of the state would curb any invassion of unsuspected members of the public that may likely invade the state through commercial operators from the neighbouring states “. The deputy governor, however, said that “the fast food operators in the state should do take-away of their foods and avoid any customers to sit down to eat in their business premises henceforth”. He dispelled rumour that the state governor, AbdulRahman AbdulRasaq has been on isolation, adding that “I want to say emphatically that, our governor is not in isolation and he is hale and hearty”. 